    <div class="quick-answer">
      <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
      <p>100 grams of protein in a day looks like: <strong>3 eggs + Greek yogurt at breakfast (35g)</strong>, a chicken breast or tuna at lunch (35g), and ground beef or salmon at dinner (30g). Three meals, real food, no supplements required — and a meaningful step up from where most men actually are.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="stat-row">
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">60–80g</div>
        <div class="stat-label">where most men over 40 actually land without tracking</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">100g</div>
        <div class="stat-label">the realistic first target — a 25–40g improvement over baseline</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">3</div>
        <div class="stat-label">meals is all it takes to hit 100g with the right anchors</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Before you can hit 120g of protein a day, you have to be able to hit 100g. And before you can hit 100g reliably, you have to know what it actually looks like on a plate.</p>

    <p>Most men who think they're eating enough protein aren't. Not because they're making bad choices — but because protein is invisible until you track it. A day that feels solid can easily land at 70g. That gap between what it feels like and what the number actually says is where muscle is quietly being lost.</p>

    <p>100g isn't the ultimate target. But it's the right starting point — achievable without overhauling your diet, and far enough above where most men are to make a real difference.</p>

    <div class="killer-line">
      Most men aren't eating badly.<br><span>They're just 30–40g short every single day.</span>
    </div>

