    <h2>What Getting From 100g to 120g Actually Takes</h2>

    <p>Once 100g feels automatic — once you're hitting it most days without thinking hard about it — the step to 120g is smaller than it sounds. The difference is roughly one additional serving.</p>

    <p>For most men that means one of these additions:</p>

    <ul style="padding-left:1.4rem; margin-bottom:20px; color:var(--text);">
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;">Add a cup of cottage cheese to lunch</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;">Go from 5oz to 6–7oz at dinner</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;">Add a protein shake as an afternoon snack</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;">Swap a light breakfast for the eggs + Greek yogurt combo</li>
    </ul>

    <p>That's it. No second diet. No new meal structure. Just one deliberate addition per day on top of the 100g foundation you've already built. For the full breakdown of what that next step looks like, see <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">what 120g of protein actually looks like</a>.</p>

    <h2>Why Tracking Is the Only Way to Know</h2>

    <p>Here's the problem with estimating protein intake: men are consistently wrong about it. Not because they're careless — but because protein is invisible in the way calories are not. A plate of food doesn't announce its protein content. A meal that feels high-protein might be 25g. Or it might be 45g. You genuinely cannot tell by looking.</p>

    <p>The men who close the gap aren't eating differently than men who don't. They're just seeing the number. Knowing at 2pm whether you're at 55g or 80g changes what you do at dinner. That mid-day visibility is worth more than any specific food choice.</p>

    <p>You don't need to track everything — just protein. One number, checked once or twice a day, tells you everything you need to know.</p>

